image.altText: Two players compete for the ball.

items.synopsis: Sweden are consistently one of the strongest teams in women's football, but are yet to go all the way in the World Cup. They get their campaign underway against South Africa.

title.children: World Cup underdogs South Africa level with Sweden in second half

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: That was scrappy! Good work down the right again from Asllani, whose cross Lebohang Ramalepe makes a mess of. Hard to tell if it dribbled in off the defender or rebounded off Rolfö, who has done very little this whole match. Anyway, that's a bit unlucky for South Africa.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 65' GOAL SWEDEN!

children.content: Good work down the right again from Asllani, whose cross
Lebohang Ramalepe makes a mess of. Hard to tell if it dribbled in off the defender or rebounded off
Rolfö, who has done very little this whole match.
Anyway, that's a bit unlucky for South Africa.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: HUGE! It was made by Kgatlana who streaked past Ilestedt, who looked like she was standing still in defence. The shot was parried by the keeper but Hildah Magaia bundled it over the line, copping a bit of an injury in the process. 54-ranked South Africa have the lead over the world number 3!
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 48' GOOOAL SOUTH AFRICA!

props.alt: Hildah Magaia lying on the ground in goal

children.content: Ilestedt, who looked like she was standing still in defence. The shot was parried by the keeper but
Hildah Magaia bundled it over the line, copping a bit of an injury in the process.
54-ranked South Africa have the lead over the world number 3!

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Another example of the heavily favoured side struggling to break down their opponents. South Africa have been dominant but unable to create any really clear chances, aside from on corners. South Africa have not sat back and defended, either, they've looked decent on th counter. It sets up a fascinating second half.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: HALF-TIME: Sweden 0 - 0 South Africa

image.altText: police and forensic officers at the secne of a shooting

items.synopsis: Two men are in a critical condition and a woman is seriously injured in the city's south-west after Sydney's latest public shooting.

title.children: Three people in hospital, two critical, after 'targeted' shooting at Greenacre in Sydney

image.altText: job advertisements page of the Courier Mail

items.synopsis: Despite the RBA's attempt to slow the economy down by rapidly hiking interest rates, the unemployment rate has averaged 3.5 per cent since July last year. So, when will the unemployment rate start to rise, if at all, asks Gareth Hutchens.

title.children: How long can the unemployment rate stay near 3.5 per cent?

image.altText: A group of musicians wearing black and white clothing play in front of a large black and white screen.

items.synopsis: The band releases a statement saying "due to current circumstances, it is impossible to proceed with the scheduled shows".

title.children: The 1975 cancel shows in Taiwan, Indonesia after Malaysia ban them for same-sex kiss at festival

image.altText: A man in a hat stands beside a woman in a green shirt.

items.synopsis: Spring Ridge hasn't had a doctor for 30 years, but that all changed when a local farmer met a pharmacist.

title.children: When a farmer and a pharmacist fell in love, they never imagined the impact it would have

image.altText: A blond woman taking a selfie outside with a bearded man next to her and two girls climbing on their back above them

items.synopsis: Influenza case numbers are soaring around the country, with young people and children the hardest hit. Some experts say it is time to make better of use of antivirals.

title.children: 'Simply too late' flu season is so bad this year some experts are calling for more antiviral use

image.altText: Sussan Ley wears a white jacket and looks off camera.

items.synopsis: The most senior female politician in the Liberal Party, Ms Ley faced a similar challenge in the lead-up to the 2022 federal election before Scott Morrison intervened. It is unclear if Peter Dutton will do the same as his predecessor.

title.children: Sussan Ley says she has Dutton's support amid 'unusual' preselection challenge

image.altText: A waist-down photo of a person who is wearing a uniform carrying a big leather bag in each hand

items.synopsis: The heavy black bag carried by military aides who follow closely in the president's footsteps has been shrouded in secrecy for decades. Little is known about the contents of the bag, as most documents about it remain classified, but one nuclear war researcher has dug deep into its history.

title.children: The 'nuclear football' follows the US president everywhere. Here's the story behind it

image.altText: A man on a stretcher is carried up the narrow bus steps

items.synopsis: On the front lines of Vladimir Putin's war in Ukraine, soldiers are facing a brutal onslaught. It's up to a volunteer team of medics, the Hospitallers Battalion, to evacuate the wounded back to safety in a race against the clock.

title.children: If you're wounded in Ukraine's brutal war, Lidia and her high-tech bus are your best hope

image.altText: A woman in casual clothes standing on a road on her Blue Mountains property

items.synopsis: NSW fire crews have already responded to more than 800 grass, scrub and bushfires this month. And communities like Susan Alexander's are turning their attention to preparing their properties for the coming summer.

title.children: Susan lost everything in the 2019 NSW fires — she's worried it's going to happen again this year

image.altText: Margot Robbie in a scene from Barbie and Cillian Murphy in a scene from Oppenheimer.

items.synopsis: Two of the year's most anticipated movies came out this weekend. Early estimates from the US put Barbie ahead in the box office takings.

title.children: Early figures from 'Barbenheimer' weekend put Barbie ahead of Oppenheimer

image.altText: A Melbourne AFL player reacts as he celebrates a goal.

title.children: AFL live: Demons meet Crows as Giants continue winning streak

image.altText: Two Wests Tigers NRLW players embrace and smile after a try.

title.children: Wests Tigers, Sharks make winning NRLW debuts

image.altText: Iannotta

title.children: She scored our first goal in Women's World Cup history — but we can't show you video of the moment

image.altText: A man stands over an anvil with a hammer in hand, next to a sign that reads 'Your future needs you. Your past does not'.

title.children: Forging helped Dean with his PTSD. Now he is helping other veterans heal through blacksmithing

image.altText: A man, wearing a black T-shirt, holds out a cup of yellow ice cream

items.synopsis: Iranian migrant Kambiz Seyedghalouri and his wife, Sara Minagar, leave behind the political turmoil of their home country to open a chocolate and gelato franchise in Wollongong. In 2021, Iran supplied the second-largest number of business migrants to Australia.

title.children: Swapping dentistry for gelato, migrants build new Australian business

image.altText: An Indigenous AFL player for Port Adelaide bends down to grab the ball as a Collingwood player closes in behind him.

items.synopsis: Port Adelaide forward Willie Rioli receives racist messages online after his side's narrow two-point defeat to AFL premiership favourites Collingwood.

title.children: Port Adelaide forward Willie Rioli hit with racist online abuse after Collingwood game

image.altText: Aerial photo of beach to the hinterland.

items.synopsis: A developer wants to build thousands of homes on the Sunshine Coast but the council says the proposed estate will clash with an emerging housing project nearby and is not a solution to the current housing crisis.

title.children: Sunshine Coast Council opposes housing estate, says it clashes with another and risks the environment

image.altText: A woman in a green dress with a buzzcut looks back at the camera in the middle of a grassy field

items.synopsis: Some young feminists in China are rebelling against mainstream beauty standards by embracing buzz cuts and ditching make-up.

title.children: Why young women in China are ditching 'beauty duty'

image.altText: Four retro video games cases

title.children: Why are staff at one of Australia's national institutions playing video games on the job?

image.altText: A great white shark looking at the camera almost looking like its smiling with its mouth open.

title.children: Ever thought about cage-diving with great white sharks? Some people want you to think twice

image.altText: A man in a hat and blue shirts sits in a hay shed.

items.synopsis: As an El Niño looms and fears of drought creep in, farmers and hay suppliers in the Hunter and New England are struggling to find local stock feed.

title.children: Last year northern NSW was in flood. Now it's so dry farmers are trucking in hay at 'astronomical' prices

image.altText: Water

items.synopsis: What do you get if you put the defending world champion, defending Olympic champion and current world record holder together in the pool? Arguably one of the most anticipated races of all time.

title.children: Swimming had its Race of the Century two decades ago — but the 400m free at the World Champs will run it close

image.altText: Marnus Labuschange puts on his gloves and carries his bat under his arm as he walks out to the middle

items.synopsis: Thanks to a fighting Marnus Labuschagne century — and more than a little help from the rain — Australia still holds out hope of rescuing a draw at Old Trafford, setting up yet another grandstand finish.

title.children: Labuschagne helps Australia rediscover its grit, setting up a final-day fight for the Ashes
